Analysis Note: Object Orientation across languages

Sau-Chin Chen

2021-07-21

Result marks

1. Niether the meta-analysis nor the mixed-effect model indicated a strong orientation effect across languages. 7/15 invetigated languages in sites showed positive effects; 3/9  invetigated languages on Internet showed positive effects.

2. Orientation effect is fairly weak in the the mixed-effect model included the languages and teams as the random effects. The additional analysis investigated the interaction of orientation effect and data sources indicated that responses collected from Internet is slower than the responses in the sites. Although data sources did not alter the orientation effects, the results from the two data sources better to be evaluated respectively.

3. The analysis on picture-picture verification responses showed that the imagery scores changed across the langauges. Mixed-effect models indicated that data sources did not alter the overall response time and the pattern of imagery scores.

4. In some languages that had only one team collected the data, such as Thai and Brazille Protuguse, the imgaery scores could predict the pattern of orientation effect. However, the prediction models require more tests from the same participant pools.

5.  (Exploratory analysis into a particular languages) 
- In some languages, such as English, more effects measured in the sites looks like positive, but many effects measured on Internet tend to be negative.

- Orientation effects had a wider variance from Internet than from sites.

Import raw data and lab information

In the site studies, we collected the participants’ gender and age on a splited Qualtrics form. Total 2340 participants (1104 females; averagely 21.46 years old) completed the study in each site.

Considering the online circumstance, we collected the participants’ gender and age at the end of OSWeb script. Before the study we also showed the verbal instruction to confirm the participants’ langauge proficiency. Total 1403 participants (926 females; averagely 23.75 years old) completed the study in each site.

Avalability Summary: in site data

Among the data in sites, 2014 participants finished sentence-picture verification task and passed the preregistered exclusion criterion (accuracy percentile > 70%); 2007 participants finished picture-picture verification task. Some PP data files were successfully imported after I decreased the criterion of file size. 7 participants’ data files were lost because the experimenters did not upload the files or submitted the wrong files.

Avalability Summary: osweb data

Through jatos server, 1337 participants finished sentence-picture verification task and passed the preregistered exclusion criterion (accuracy percentile > 70%); 1337 participants finished picture-picture verification task. We excluded 1 participant from USA_033 because this participant did not complete the picture-picture verification.

Avalability Summary: all data

According to our preregistered plan, each laboratory has to collect at least 50 participants. Some laboratories did not reach the minimal criterion because of the following reasons: (1)their works were interrupted by the pandemic outbreak; (2)the participants performed worse through the online study; (3) the laboratories allocated the seats for the foreign participants; (4) A language (e.g., Serbian) has a various of scripts.

Pre-analysis summary

At the end of data collection, there are 18 languages registered in this project. The collected data were from 47 laboratories and 3351 participants.

Descriptive Characteristics of Participants

Participants responded their gender and age in a open-ended questions. We extracted their responses from the Qualtric server of companion study (cite PSA 003). At the first clean cycle, we filtered the data which had the time stamps incompatible with the sentence-picture verification data. The responses of gender and age were translated on google sheet (see this link ).

Inter-lab analysis after data collection

Challenging Question: the data source is a confounding among languages and teams, the alternative analysis has to reveal the influence of data source on the preregistered analysis.

At first we manage all the data analysis as our plan. Then we evaluate the confounding as the supplemental.

1. Identify the outliers in each data set.

Because the original study evaluate RT by median, here I used Q3 to identify the outliers. By each lab, we summarised how many data beyond this criterion.

LABS <- unique(SP_V_tidy$PSA_ID)

get_intercept <- function(LAB_ID) {
  subject_nr = as.factor(subset(SP_V_tidy,PSA_ID == LAB_ID)$subject_nr) %>% levels() %>% as.numeric()
  
## Source = subset(SP_V_tidy,PSA_ID == LAB_ID)$Source

  t <- cbind(##Source,
             subject_nr,
             (lmer(response_time ~ Match + (1|subject_nr), data = subset(SP_V_tidy,PSA_ID == LAB_ID)) %>%
  coef())$subject_nr %>%
      as.tibble()%>%
  mutate(Outlier = `(Intercept)` > quantile(`(Intercept)`,probs=.75))
    )
  
  return(t)
}

outliers_table <- NULL
for(set in LABS){
  outliers_table<- get_intercept(set) %>%
    mutate(LAB = set) %>%
    rbind(outliers_table)
}

## Summarize outliers by lab
outliers_table %>%
  group_by(LAB) %>%
  summarise(N = sum(Outlier), Prop = round(sum(Outlier)/n(),2) ) %>%
  rmarkdown::paged_table(options = list(rows.print = 10))

Two kinds of datasets: No outliers; 1/4 of data were beyond criterion. Because the data were collected in the site then on the internet, we summarised the reaction times and the orientation effect (Mismatch - Match) respectively.

SP_V_tidy %>% left_join(outliers_table, by=c("PSA_ID" = "LAB", "subject_nr" = "subject_nr")) %>%
  filter(Outlier == FALSE & Source == "site") %>%
  mutate(Subject = paste0(Source,"_",PSA_ID,"_",subject_nr)) %>%
  group_by(Language, Subject, Match) %>%
  summarise(subject_M = median(response_time), subject_ACC = n()/12) %>%
  group_by(Language, Match) %>%
  summarise(N = n(), med_RT = median(subject_M), mean_ACC =   mean(subject_ACC)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Match, values_from = c(med_RT, mean_ACC)) %>%
  mutate(Effect = (med_RT_N - med_RT_Y) ) %>%
  transmute( N=N,
             Mismatch_stat = paste0(round(med_RT_N),"(",round(mean_ACC_N*100,2),")"),
             Match_stat = paste0(round(med_RT_Y),"(",round(mean_ACC_Y*100,2),")"),
             Effect = Effect) %>%
  flextable() %>% 
  set_header_labels(Language = "Language", N = "N", Mismatch_stat ="Mismatching", Match_stat = "Matching", Effect = "Orientation Effect")
SP_V_tidy %>% left_join(outliers_table, by=c("PSA_ID" = "LAB", "subject_nr" = "subject_nr")) %>%
  filter(Outlier == FALSE & Source == "osweb") %>%
mutate(Subject = paste0(Source,"_",PSA_ID,"_",subject_nr)) %>%
  group_by(Language, Subject, Match) %>%
  summarise(subject_M = median(response_time), subject_ACC = n()/12) %>%
  group_by(Language, Match) %>%
  summarise(N = n(), med_RT = median(subject_M), mean_ACC = mean(subject_ACC)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Match, values_from = c(med_RT, mean_ACC)) %>%
  mutate(Effect = (med_RT_N - med_RT_Y) ) %>%
  transmute( N=N,
             Mismatch_stat = paste0(round(med_RT_N),"(",round(mean_ACC_N*100,2),")"),
             Match_stat = paste0(round(med_RT_Y),"(",round(mean_ACC_Y*100,2),")"),
             Effect = Effect) %>%
  flextable() %>% 
  set_header_labels(Language = "Language", N = "N", Mismatch_stat ="Mismatching", Match_stat = "Matching", Effect = "Orientation Effect")

2. Meta analysis of orientation effects across lab

Overall data

Meta analysis followed Chen et al.(2020) in which they analyzed the orientation effect and object size.

## Prepare the data sets for the meta analysis

SP_V_meta_data <- SP_V_tidy %>%

Compare effect size by site and by osweb

In use of the method demonstrated on the metafor site, we compared the estimated effect size across data sources. The result showed neither data source had a larger or smaller effect size, and the estimated effect size was not significant different between the data sources. However, the variance of osweb data was significant larger than that of site data.

3. Estimate a general orientation effect

“In the mixed-effect model, we treat the laboratory and language as random effects and the match advantage of object orientations as a fixed effect.”

Planned analysis

We at first conducted the model with four random effects: participants, targets, laboratories, and languages.

We found the targets and languages were 0 because these items were tested within participant across matching and mismatching condition. According to the rules for determining the random effect structure (Barr et al., 2013), the model unnecessarily enter the units into the random structure when the units were independent with each other. Therefore we conducted the model excluded the targets and languages from the random effect structure. The analysis indicated a weak overall orientation effect.

reduced_random1.lmer = lmer(response_time ~ Match + (1|Subject) + (1|PSA_ID), data = SP_V_lme_data)

Concerned the shift of data collection method, we conducted the mixed-effect model with the fixed effect of data source. In this model the languages are nonindependent from the data source, thus the language was treated as one random effect. The analysis indicated that the responses collected in sites were faster than the responses collected on the website. As like the previous models, the overall orientation effect was weak and had no interaction with the data source.

Q: Should I separate site and osweb at the beginning? => I managed this question in the below section.

Analysis included data source

Our study had to altered the data collection method from sites to from Internet due to the pandemic situation. We conducted the mixed-effect model included the orientation effect and data source as the fixed effects. According to Jake Westfall’s suggestion on Stackoverflow, we conducted two mixed-effect models included data source as the random slopes. One model computed had the correlations of data source and the other random effects (teams, langauges), and the other had no the correlations. Each model indicated the significant difference between the sites and Internet and no interaction of the orientation effect and the data sources. The results was consistent with the meta analysis on the estimated effect size and with the published mega studies comparing the results from sites and from Internet (Anwyl-Irvine et al., 2020; Bridges et al., 2020).

SP_V_lme_data$r_Source = if_else(SP_V_lme_data$Source == "site",1,-1)

4. Analysis on imagery scores

Overall estimation and test

“… we compute an imagery score by taking the elapsed verification time between the orientation settings of critical object pictures (identical, different).”

initial assumption Imagery scores (elapsed responses times from different to identical orientation settings) are the dependent measurement of picture-picture verification task. Initially we assumed the results of every language group would be nearly equal. Our exploratory goal is to test the predictions of imagery scores on the orientation effect.

Below table we summarized the imagery scores from the data excluded the outliers we identified in the first part: “Identify the outliers in each data set”.

## Dataset for traditional ANOVA
PP_aov_data <- PP_tidy %>% left_join(outliers_table, by=c("PSA_ID" = "LAB", "subject_nr" = "subject_nr")) %>%  ## filter the outliers by SP_V data
  filter(Outlier == FALSE) %>%
mutate(Subject = paste0(Source,"_",PSA_ID,"_",subject_nr)) %>%
  group_by(Source, Language, PSA_ID, Subject, Identical) %>%
  summarise(subject_M = median(response_time), subject_ACC = n()/12) 

## Dataset for mixed-effect model
PP_lme_data <- PP_tidy %>% left_join(outliers_table, by=c("PSA_ID" = "LAB", "subject_nr" = "subject_nr")) %>%  ## filter the outliers by SP_V data
  filter(Outlier == FALSE) %>%
mutate(Subject = paste0(Source,"_",PSA_ID,"_",subject_nr))

## 
PP_aov_data %>% group_by(Language, Identical) %>%
  summarise(N = n(), med_RT = median(subject_M), mean_ACC = mean(subject_ACC)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Identical, values_from = c(med_RT, mean_ACC)) %>%
  mutate(Imagery = (med_RT_N - med_RT_Y) ) %>%
  transmute( N=N,
             Mismatch_stat = paste0(round(med_RT_N),"(",round(mean_ACC_N*100,2),")"),
             Match_stat = paste0(round(med_RT_Y),"(",round(mean_ACC_Y*100,2),")"),
             Imagery = Imagery) %>%
  flextable() %>% 
  set_header_labels(Language = "Language", N = "N", Mismatch_stat ="Different", Match_stat = "Identical", Effect = "Imagery Score")

Imagery scores among the languages and the laboratories

“The first step compares the imagery scores among the languages and the laboratories with the analysis of variance. The results will indicate the generalizability of mental rotation among languages.”

  • Traditional ANOVA

Because languages and laboratories are nonindependent with each other, we analyzed each interaction with orientation setting (presented pictures in same/different orientations) separately.

The traditional ANOVA of languages and orientation setting indicated the interaction which means the imagery scores were higher in some languages.

Q from Pat: some convergence problems in your models (ex this warning about negative eigenvalues is a big deal & i would try refitting the model, either by changing the optimizer — bobyqa often works well — or by simplifying it). => When I input the tidy data instead of the summarized data and exclude the random slopes, the output had no message like “failed to converge”.

Considering the additional data source, we further conducted the mixed-effect model to evaluate the confounding of languages and sites. Our reason depended on our purpose to evaluate results of traditional ANOVA. In the first model, the orientation setting are the only one fixed effect; languages and sites are the random effects. The result indicated that languages and sites influenced little on the overall effect of orientation setting.

The final question was removed because the above analysis has verified the unequal imagery scores among the langauges.

We learned the two facts from the analyses on the interactions of imagery scores and the potential variables: languages, datasets/teams, and data sources. Firstly we could exclude the sites and the data sources as the confounding factor altered the imagery scores. On the other hand, the interaction of orientation setting and languages supported the prediction model for a particular language rather than the prediction model for many languages.

Regression model to predict orientation effect.

“In the second step, the imagery scores and languages will be the predictor in the regression model that uses the match advantage as the dependent variable. This regression model will be the prediction model for the match advantage of object orientation in future studies.”

The above analysis addresses the some languages showed larger imagery scores than the others. The data sources did not alter the imagery scores but alter the orientation effect. We will build the regression models to predict the orientation effect for the specific languages by the data source.

For each data source, we at first integrated the data of sentence-picture verification and picture-picture verification. Because the random intercept of items is zero, we computed the orientation effects and the imagery scores by participant.

## I will merge the SP_V and PP data by participants' mean response times
model_site_data <- (SP_V_tidy %>% left_join(outliers_table, by=c("PSA_ID" = "LAB", "subject_nr" = "subject_nr")) %>%
  filter(Outlier == FALSE & Source == "site") %>%
  mutate(Subject = paste0(Source,"_",PSA_ID,"_",subject_nr)) %>%
  group_by(Language, Subject, Match) %>%
  summarise(subject_M = median(response_time)) %>%

  pivot_wider(names_from = Match, values_from = c(subject_M)) %>%
  mutate(Effect = (N - Y) )) %>%
left_join(
(PP_aov_data %>%
  select(-subject_ACC) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Identical, values_from = subject_M) %>%
  mutate(Imagery = (N - Y))),

)

  select(-subject_ACC) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Identical, values_from = subject_M) %>%
  mutate(Imagery = (N - Y))),
by = c("Language","Subject")
)
  • Prediction models for site data

We plotted the regression lines of orientation effect and imagery scores by each language respectively. There was no a general pattern appeared across the languages.

lang_sets <- unique(model_site_data$Language)

  site_plots[[lang]] <-  ggplot(subset(model_site_data, Language == lang), aes(Imagery, Effect)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) + 
    labs(title=lang)
}

cowplot::plot_grid(plotlist = site_plots, ncol = 5)
